         <h1>Colin Rowe, Architecture Professor, Dies at 79 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Colin Rowe , a historian and teacher whose ideas helped to shape the thinking of some of today 's most prominent American architects , died on Friday in Arlington , Va . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 79 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was respiratory failure after a stroke suffered in May , said Judy DiMaio , a friend . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Rowe , a native of Britain , was the Andrew Dickson White Professor of Architecture at Cornell University , where he taught from 1962 until his retirement in 1990 . <br><blue>5</blue>His students included many architects who became leaders in the profession . <br><blue>6</blue>Ada Louise Huxtable , architecture critic at The Wall Street Journal and formerly an architecture critic at The New York Times , once wrote that Mr. Rowe and Vincent Scully were the most influential historians of their time . <br><blue>7</blue>Where Mr. Scully exhorted his troops from the lecture platform at Yale , Mr. Rowe was likely to hold forth in his living room in Ithaca , N.Y. , a book-lined retreat furnished with 18th-century mechanical chairs . <br><blue>8</blue>Mr. Rowe 's literary output was not prodigious . <br><blue>9</blue>His books include '' The Mathematics of the Ideal Villa and Other Essays '' ( 1976 ) , '' Collage City , '' written with Fred Koetter ( 1978 ) , and '' The Architecture of Good Intentions '' ( 1994 ) . <br><blue>10</blue>In 1996 Mr. Rowe published a three-volume collection of essays and memoirs titled '' As I Was Saying . '' <br><blue>11</blue>At the time of his death , he was working on a book about Italian Renaissance architecture , his favorite period . <br><blue>12</blue>But his real legacy is to be found in the minds of students and colleagues who became distinguished teachers in their own right at Yale , Princeton , Harvard , the University of Pennsylvania and other elite schools of architecture . <br><blue>13</blue>Mr. Rowe 's impact can also be seen in some of the late century 's most impressive buildings , including the Getty Center in Los Angeles , designed by Richard Meier , and the Wexner Center for the Arts in Columbus , Ohio , designed by Peter Eisenman . <br><blue>14</blue>Mr. Rowe 's significance largely revolved around the issue of formalism . <br><blue>15</blue>Should visual and spatial forms be seen as architecture 's irreducible essence , or does form represent only one layer in a set of values that includes psychological meaning , social intention , political ideology and other human factors at work in the urban whole ? <br><blue>16</blue>In the 1950 's and 60 's Mr. Rowe strongly favored a formalist approach to architectural analysis . <br><blue>17</blue>This was highly compelling to young architects who hoped to retrieve something of value from the declining modern movement . <br><blue>18</blue>By then modernism had become the preferred style of corporate America . <br><blue>19</blue>The modern aesthetic had been further debased by dimly executed glass skyscrapers and other poor imitations of modern prototypes . <br><blue>20</blue>At this critical moment Mr. Rowe promoted the idea that architecture could renew itself by embracing the idea of form for form 's sake . <br><hr><br><blue>1(1)</blue>: <m_str>modernism</m_str> (18_3) 	<br><blue>2(1)</blue>: <m_str>His students</m_str> (5_1) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>This</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>a formalist approach</m_str> (16_12) 	<br><blue>4(4)</blue>: <m_str>Vincent Scully</m_str> (6_29) 	<m_str>Mr. Scully</m_str> (7_2) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (7_5) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (7_22) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>Yale</m_str> (7_12) 	<m_str>Yale</m_str> (12_25) 	<br><blue>6(1)</blue>: <m_str>Richard Meier</m_str> (13_30) 	<br><blue>7(1)</blue>: <m_str>Peter Eisenman</m_str> (13_47) 	<br><blue>8(4)</blue>: <m_str>itself</m_str> (20_14) 	<m_str>architecture</m_str> (12_40) 	<m_str>architecture 's</m_str> (15_9) 	<m_str>architecture</m_str> (20_11) 	<br><blue>9(14)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (11_5) 	<m_str>Mr. Rowe</m_